    "body": "## Problem\n\nWhen `cmdheight=0`, running `:res 10` (or any value that shrinks the window) causes Neovim to increase `cmdheight` to compensate for the lost space, instead of keeping `cmdheight=0`.\n\n## Steps to reproduce\n\n```bash\nnvim --clean -c \"set cmdheight=0\" -c \"res 10\"\n```\n\nThen check: `:echo &cmdheight` → returns `13` (or similar large value) instead of `0`.\n\n### More detailed results\n\n| Condition | cmdheight result |\n|-----------|-----------------|\n| `set cmdheight=0` → `:vsplit` | 0 (OK) |\n| `set cmdheight=0` → `:res 10` | 13 (unexpected) |\n| `set cmdheight=0` → `:vsplit` → `:res 10` | 13 (unexpected) |\n| `set cmdheight=0` → `:split` → `:res 10` | 0 (OK) |\n\nWith a horizontal split, Neovim can take space from the other window, so `cmdheight` stays at 0. But in a single window or vertical split, Neovim increases `cmdheight` to make room — and never restores it.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\n`cmdheight` should remain `0` after `:res`. Neovim should either refuse to shrink below the minimum height or find another way to reclaim space without altering `cmdheight`.\n\n## Actual behavior\n\n`cmdheight` jumps to a large value (e.g., 13 or 30 depending on terminal size) and stays there permanently.\n\n## Context\n\nThis was initially reported as a mini.animate bug ([echasnovski/mini.nvim#2368](https://github.com/nvim-mini/mini.nvim/issues/2368)), but the maintainer confirmed it reproduces with `nvim --clean` — it is a Neovim core behavior.\n\n## Version\n\n```\nNVIM v0.12.0\n```",
